{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17536919","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17536919"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:11:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:11:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15830"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15830","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15830"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.11,0.52,0.03,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8521"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62792"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8521","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8521"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15830"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48241"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"274"},{"type":"tags","id":"1206"},{"type":"tags","id":"2101"},{"type":"tags","id":"2770"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"5797"},{"type":"tags","id":"6275"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20456"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43596"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62792","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62792"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department following a fall. She reports a three-week history of worsening left hip pain prior to the fall, and is now unable to mobilise. She has a medical history of osteoarthritis, rheumatoid arthritis, and type 2 diabetes. Her regular medications include methotrexate, prednisolone, and metformin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears uncomfortable. Her pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. There is tenderness over the anterior aspect of her left hip. Pain is exacerbated by active hip flexion and passive hip extension, often accompanied by a snapping sound. Hip range of motion is otherwise preserved. There is no leg length discrepancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInitial blood tests including full blood count, C-reactive protein, and electrolytes are within normal limits. Left hip and pelvis X-ray shows no fracture or other acute abnormality, but there is generalised changes consistent with osteoarthritis..\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Computed tomography scan of the hip","Ultrasound of the hip","Magnetic resonance imaging of the hip","Hip aspiration","Bone scan"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features suggestive of iliopsoas bursitis, including anterior hip pain that is worse with active hip flexion and passive extension. Given her risk factors including rheumatoid arthritis and recent fall, appropriate imaging is essential to confirm the diagnosis and exclude other pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance imaging\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next investigation as it provides detailed soft tissue imaging that can identify bursitis, tendinopathy, and any associated pathology. It can also detect early osteonecrosis, stress fractures, and other conditions that may not be visible on plain radiographs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography\u003C/strong\u003E scanning would be more appropriate if there was concern about bony pathology not visible on plain films. However, CT has limited soft tissue resolution compared to MRI and would not be as useful for diagnosing iliopsoas bursitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBone scan\u003C/strong\u003E would be more appropriate if there was concern about infection, occult fracture, or metastatic disease. However, it lacks the anatomical detail needed to diagnose soft tissue pathology such as bursitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound\u003C/strong\u003E can be useful for diagnosing superficial soft tissue pathology and guiding therapeutic injections. However, the deep location of the iliopsoas bursa makes ultrasound less reliable than MRI for this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHip aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if there was concern about septic arthritis or crystal arthropathy. However, the normal inflammatory markers and absence of systemic symptoms make infection less likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Iliopsoas bursitis presents with anterior hip pain, worse on active hip flexion and passive extension.","MRI is the gold standard imaging modality for diagnosing iliopsoas bursitis.","Hip pain in elderly patients requires careful evaluation to exclude serious pathology including fracture, infection, and malignancy."],"references":["Anderson CN. Iliopsoas: Pathology, Diagnosis, and Treatment. Clin Sports Med. 2016 Jul;35(3):419-433. doi: 10.1016/j.csm.2016.02.009. Epub 2016 Mar 28. PMID: 27343394. Available online at ; https://toa.com/storage/wysiwyg/Anderson%20Iliopsoas%20Pathology%20Diagnosis%20and%20Treatment.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48241"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15830"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48241","links":{"self":"https://a